Nickel mining is also important for the province, but mainly concentrated in Morawali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Mitigation Agency, Palu and Dongala have been hit several times in the past 100 years by a tsunami.
In 1938, more than 200 people died in Dongala from the tsunami, and hundreds of homes were destroyed.
A tsunami also struck the western part of Dongal in 1996, resulting in nine deaths.
Indonesia is in a seismically active Pacific fire ring and is regularly rocked by earthquakes.
The following is a list of major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A strong earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in northern Sumatra on December 26 caused a tsunami that hit 14 countries, resulting in 226,000 deaths along the entire coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes swept the west coast of Sumatra in late March-early April.
Hundreds of people have died on Nias Island, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake occurred south of Java, Indonesia's most densely populated island, causing a tsunami that swept to the south coast, killing about 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake occurred in Padang City, the capital of West Sumatra Province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake occurred on one of the Mentawai Islands outside of Sumatra, causing a tsunami up to 10 metres high that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A weak earthquake pummeled the regency of Podzi Jaya in Aceh province, causing havoc and panic as people were reminded of the devastation resulting from the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time the tsunami did not come, but more than 100 people died under the ruins of the buildings.
2018: Strong earthquakes swept over the tourist island of Indonesia's Lambok, killing more than 500 people, mainly in the north of the island.
